EditorData.NodeContext: Listing off all the aspects of her terrible reputation, humourously making the point that there's more to her than that.

Text.Value: We've crossed paths over the years. Two hands trying to steer the city - just not always in the same direction.

EditorData.NodeContext: Speaking of Jaheira, for whom she has equal parts admiration as a fellow protector of the city (as she sees it), and irritation for being a do-gooder who gets in her way

Text.Value: Huh.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly more inflected grunt of mute surprise.

Text.Value: Hi there. I'm a friend of Jaheira's.

EditorData.logicalname: NF NEVER TOLD US TO BRING JAHEIRA

Text.Value: The Guild is many things, but it's not an army. If the Absolute keeps pushing in on our territory, then I need a little weight to push back.

EditorData.NodeContext: Distaste - we've broached a topic she's not pleased to talk about, but will

Text.Value: You still look like you need a rest, grandmother. Anything I can do to take that wrinkle from your brow?

EditorData.NodeContext: Sourly amused, certain Jaheira is about to be a pain her arse somehow.

Text.Value: My fame precedes me. That, or you've been spying on me.
Rather than stuffing you in a box and dropping you into the river, you mean?

EditorData.NodeContext: Casual, but boiling with fury underneath

Text.Value: If we take a little tribute in return, or tie strings of service to those we help, well - what of it? So long as we're working as one, it all runs quick, quiet, and clean.

EditorData.NodeContext: Acknowledging the Guild's criminal aspects, not shying away

Text.Value: We're practically sisters! So much so, I even stopped trying to have her killed a few years back.

EditorData.NodeContext: Exaggerated affection

Text.Value: The leader of some new crew that's intent on paining my arse.
What? I was trying to spy a nice warm spot for Boo's bedding.

EditorData.NodeContext: Abrupt, absolutely was not listening to Jaheira and Nine-Fingers discuss him.

Text.Value: So what do you plan to do, now that you know?
How is it you know so much about the cult of the Absolute and its leaders?
You might have removed Gortash, but Orin's Faceless are still circling.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim amusement - we've asked for an update on a terrible situation

Text.Value: You seem to know quite a bit about the cult.
You think he's a cultist?
They seemed like upstanding citizens.
Deal with it yourself.
Good. Because I've already got more enemies than I do fingers.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Oh, how nice you're not going to kill me today'

Text.Value: All I know is that on every scrap of ground he takes from me, the cult of the Absolute soon starts sprouting.

EditorData.NodeContext: annoyed

Text.Value: And with a familiar face in tow.

EditorData.NodeContext: Tone sharpening just enough to be threatening - 'I let you walk in, but depending what you say, I might not let you walk out again'
EditorData.logicalname: PLAYER MET NF ALREADY, WEREN'T TOLD TO BRING JAHEIRA

Text.Value: Minsc was never one to need much persuading. Not when it came to spilling my people's blood.
But it's not that Watch that keeps the peace, or gives justice to any Baldurian who asks, whether they can pay for it or not. It's us.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quiet, defiant pride - the image she paints of the Guild is one that the city's upper crust would scoff at, but one she fervently believes in

Text.Value: They got a payday out of me.
In his short reign, the Stone Lord and his crew have earned a reputation. Pure brutality. No survivors. And where he mows my people down, this ripe little cult takes root.

EditorData.NodeContext: Controlled anger - she does not like being put on the back foot

Text.Value: I'm here to stop the Absolute. I won't be questioned by you.
The Rats usually kept a lid on their nastier notions, but with the Stone Lord business distracting me... some are starting to test the leash.

EditorData.NodeContext: Rueful - her control is slipping because of the cult

Text.Value: If he was just another upstart who didn't like paying Guild dues, fair enough. But he and his crew make no demands, leave no survivors to pass on a message.

EditorData.NodeContext: Relaying the threat the Stone Lord poses

Text.Value: Am I interrupting? Your guards just let me pass.
You have, but don't be so quick to bat away a helping hand. You'll find few enough of them in this city.

EditorData.NodeContext: Amused at our self-belief - not dismissing it, but knows no one can fight the Absolute alone

Text.Value: But not for much longer. We have word on where he plans to hit next - and he'll find us ready to hit back this time.

EditorData.NodeContext: Getting the anger under control - she has it all in hand.

Text.Value: The Watch, the Council, even the Parliament of Peers - they're the clean face they want the world to see.
So tell me - why would you kill Ketheric and chase his co-conspirators to the city, only to turn on us at the last moment? Why let Minsc get away?

EditorData.NodeContext: Faux puzzlement: ' please explain the dumb thing you did, because I'm sure there's some secret genius to it'

Text.Value: And I hear you're the one who killed him.
Unless she's taken to dyeing her hair, I'd call it accurate enough.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging

Text.Value: I killed them all.
Because I'm curious. About why you're here - and who it is you've brought with you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Tone sharpening just enough to be threatening - 'I let you walk in, but depending what you say, I might not let you walk out again'

Text.Value: But if there's a tainted elder brain slopping around below my city, I think we need one another more than ever.
Because it's always the Dead bloody Three - has-been half-gods who can't help but make their irrelevance everyone else's problem.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quiet eye-rolling at the dead three - they're three particular gods who always target her city, and always end up being foiled.

Text.Value: As, it seems, do you. I already know the only thing about you that I need to.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not overly complimentary - just stating facts

Text.Value: And when we're sitting in your stronghold, I'll give a good slippery shite about what you want.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sharp, letting her anger show - not freaking out, just putting us in our place before returning to her normal tone.

Text.Value: I didn't say 'forgive'. Seize the building. Arm any children old enough. If they protect what's mine, we'll consider that a start on what's owed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Cutting Uktar off. Making it clear she's not soft-hearted - her plan is even more pragmatic than his

Text.Value: You can help a companion of mine who needs information - Jaheira.

EditorData.logicalname: DOESN'T KNOW AMBUSH, JAHEIRA MENTIONED NF

Text.Value: Oh? You've got some juicy little tidbit I haven't heard yet?

EditorData.NodeContext: Actual interest - rare enough for her to hear something she doesn't already know

Text.Value: I'm terribly sentimental. Case in point - I've just let a Harper walk through my Guildhall, noticeably unholed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Faux-earnestess.

Text.Value: The Stone Lord's fate is sealed. We have a bigger war to fight. I'd rather turn our talk to that, but if you need a moment, Jaheira...

EditorData.NodeContext: Her mind isn't going to be changed and she's moving on. But her urging for us to keep it is genuinely sincere - she respects Jaheira, and doesn't want this to get ugly.

Text.Value: How do you know who I am?
I could, but she wouldn't thank either of us for that. Trust me.
What makes you think he's joined the Absolute? Maybe he just doesn't like thieves.
'Somewhat spiky'? In the same way a morningstar is, yes.
Bring her here. Whatever questions she has, she'll want to hear the answers directly from me.
We know he plans on something higher profile next - a little operation the Guild has running in the Counting House.
It makes sense, Jaheira. We know the cult can be... persuasive.
Do any more, and the Guild might have to take a special interest in you. Understood? Great.

EditorData.NodeContext: Tightly controlled anger - a threat to let us know the matter is closed

Text.Value: You owe me a gold piece, grandmother.

EditorData.NodeContext: Idle surprise, as if unconcerned to see Jaheira walk into her hall. 'Grandmother' is faux-respectful, not overly sentimental

Text.Value: You know Jaheira?
Who is this Stone Lord that has your Guild running scared?
When I heard you died out in the wilderness, I made an offering at Kelemvor's well.

EditorData.NodeContext: Idle surprise, as if unconcerned to see Jaheira walk into her hall.

Text.Value: Hah! The best in the city, under or above. So smart a mouth as yours would enjoy it, provided you keep all your teeth.

EditorData.NodeContext: Genuine bark of a laugh - she appreciates audacity, but is also warning not to go too far

Text.Value: But it takes thugs to keep order outside the walls. The Fist only go there for good lawless fun.

EditorData.NodeContext: Acknowleding that her people are thugs, but it's thugs she needs in that neighborhood

Text.Value: Simple enough, I reckon. Now - war to be fought. You need anything?

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging, pragmatic - our big secret doesn't change the war she has to fight

Text.Value: I need to see Jaheira. Just so happens, she'll want to see me too.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reminding us of what she asked

Text.Value: The Stone Lord's fate is sealed. We have a bigger war to fight. I'd rather turn our talk to that, but if you need a moment, Jaheira...

EditorData.NodeContext: Her mind isn't going to be changed and she's moving on. But her urging for us to keep it is genuinely sincere - she respects Jaheira, and doesn't want this to get ugly.

Text.Value: I need to speak with her. She's still getting the lay of the land, I expect - I have information that might help with that.
I need information.
I didn't turn on anyone - but Minsc is not the enemy.
Aye. Transport corridors. Not the most glamorous targets, but without the vine, the cherries shrivel and die.
I need some information from you first.
Leave.
Now - is there anything else you need?
Hah. Which part? The Stone Lord's hollowed this place out - half my crews are fled or in hiding.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim amusement - we've asked for an update on a terrible situation

Text.Value: I ran into some of your thugs - the Rivington Rats?

EditorData.logicalname: Response to dealing with Rivington rats

Text.Value: How's your fight against the Absolute going?
Kill the Absolute, and keep the big bald berserker out of trouble. We'll find out if either of those things is possible.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry - that one task is plenty

Text.Value: You've dealt with Orin, but Gortash still clutters my streets with his toy soldiers.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim amusement - we've asked for an update on a terrible situation

Text.Value: I'd like to know more about the Guild.
We know where he plans to hit next - a little operation the Guild have running in the city's Counting House.
Against my own city? Careful - you're in very real danger of hurting my feelings.

EditorData.NodeContext: Still mild, but an edge coming through - we do NOT want to offend her

Text.Value: As you like. I always do. My welcome stands - maybe I'm just nicer than you are.
And you're Nine-Fingers Keene, Guildmaster.
I won't tax your hospitality too long, Nine-Fingers. I'm searching for Minsc of Rashemen.
In return - if I can offer aid, information, just ask.

Synopsis:
CINE ARTIST - PLEASE CONTACT WRITER! (RUAIRI)
The flow looks complex due to integration of an OM, but is relatively simple after the first stage.
The first stage is always Nine-Fingers arguing with her underling Uktar, who always leaves before the first player QNs.

After that, Jaheira's OM is prioritised, where Nine-Fingers tells her that Minsc is the Stone Lord. The Guild have set a trap to kill him, and she doesn't want Jaheira to interfere.

After that, Nine-Fingers introduces herself to the player and can be asked questions about the city. If Jaheira's OM has not triggered yet, that takes priority on any subsequent meetings.
